<figureCitation id="130D2A1BFFEAFFC2ABCCFB89126944CD" box="[728,860,1146,1173]" captionStart-0="Fig" captionStart-1="Fig" captionStart-2="Fig" captionStart-3="Fig" captionStart-4="Fig" captionStartId-0="58.[189,232,1964,1990]" captionStartId-1="59.[189,232,1895,1921]" captionStartId-2="60.[189,232,1895,1921]" captionStartId-3="61.[189,232,1930,1956]" captionStartId-4="62.[189,232,847,873]" captionTargetBox-0="[191,1397,621,1923]" captionTargetBox-1="[192,1397,345,1852]" captionTargetBox-2="[192,1396,294,1853]" captionTargetBox-3="[192,1396,372,1886]" captionTargetBox-4="[192,1368,313,751]" captionTargetId-0="figure@58.[188,1400,618,1926]" captionTargetId-1="figure@59.[189,1399,342,1854]" captionTargetId-2="figure@60.[189,1398,291,1855]" captionTargetId-3="figure@61.[189,1399,369,1889]" captionTargetId-4="figure@62.[190,1399,311,806]" captionTargetPageId-0="58" captionTargetPageId-1="59" captionTargetPageId-2="60" captionTargetPageId-3="61" captionTargetPageId-4="62" captionText-0="Fig. 17. Adelges (Sacciphantes) abietis (Linnaeus, 1758), galls on Picea abies. A–B. Almost full-grown. C. Half-grown. Colouration typical for galls growing in open sites. Scale bars: 10 mm." captionText-1="Fig. 18. Adelges (Sacciphantes) abietis (Linnaeus, 1758), galls on Picea abies. A–D. Galls from different sites showing variation in colouration. A. From a semi-open site. B. In semi-shade. C–D. In deep shade. E–F. Newly opened galls with exuviae and alate gallicolae around. G–H. Galls from previous summer. Note the colony of Cinara pilicornis (Hartig, 1841) on the stem in A. Scale bars: 10 mm." captionText-2="Fig. 19. Adelges (Sacciphantes) abietis (Linnaeus, 1758) on Picea abies. The gallicolae fly only a very short distance from their mother gall (A–B), where they lay their eggs (C–E). A majority of the eggs remain on the mother’s dorsum, sheltered by her wings. Newly hatched alatae are red-brown (F–G), head and thorax darkening with age (I)." captionText-3="Fig. 20. Adelges (Sacciphantes) abietis (Linnaeus, 1758) on Picea abies in winter. A. First instar exuvium and second instar nymphs. B. First instar exuvium. C–D. Second instar nymphs, in D with wax filaments worn off." captionText-4="Fig. 21. Adelges (Sacciphantes) abietis (Linnaeus, 1758). A. Adult pseudofundatrix. B. Antenna of alate gallicola. (After Börner 1908, redrawn and modified.)" figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3834383" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3834385" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3834387" figureDoi-3="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3834389" figureDoi-4="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3834391" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/3834383/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/3834385/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/3834387/files/figure.png" httpUri-3="https://zenodo.org/record/3834389/files/figure.png" httpUri-4="https://zenodo.org/record/3834391/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Figs 17–21</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
